<div id="review_35516126" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/35516126" />
    <a title="Randy" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1628910-randy"><img alt="Randy" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1224390414p2/1628910.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/35516126?book_show_action=true">Oct 16, 2008</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Randy" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Randy" href="/user/show/1628910-randy">Randy</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1628910-randy?shelf=not-sci-fi">not-sci-fi</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer35516126" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10515671098963147936">Never been a fan of wrestling. Yes, I just started a review with a segment and not a sentence. In truth, I knew who Mick Foley was before I read this book because a friend and fellow comedian was obsessed with wrestling. He handed me this weighty tome and declared it &quot;the best wrestling book ever&quot;.<br/><br/>&quot;Wow&quot;, I thought. &quot;That&apos;s a bit like saying Paris Hilton is the queen of the spoiled, rich whores.&quot; No offense to whores. Anyway, I got about twenty-five pages in before I understood that beneath that </span>
  <span id="freeText10515671098963147936" style="display:none">Never been a fan of wrestling. Yes, I just started a review with a segment and not a sentence. In truth, I knew who Mick Foley was before I read this book because a friend and fellow comedian was obsessed with wrestling. He handed me this weighty tome and declared it "the best wrestling book ever".<br /><br />"Wow", I thought. "That's a bit like saying Paris Hilton is the queen of the spoiled, rich whores." No offense to whores. Anyway, I got about twenty-five pages in before I understood that beneath that mask of scars and missing teeth, there lurked a budding writer in Mick Foley. He has now gone on to refine that talent (likely with the same, unwavering determination he displays in Blood And Sweatsocks - his preferred title for this book). Also, it occurred to me the many parallels between the struggling, road-wrestler and the struggling road-comic, but I'll leave that aside and stick to the germane. <br /><br />An autobiography that reads like a Hollywood feel-goodery, Blood And Sweatsocks covers Mick Foley from his awkward high-school days to the pinnacle of his career as a professional wrestler. Caveat Emptor: This is not a wrestling book. It's a tale of determination, sacrifice, pain, and grit standing triumphant in he face of great adversity.<br /><br />The only real problem I've ever had with the book is Foley's aw-shucks humility and demurral. He describes himself as having a thimble-full of talent. Sorry, Mick. You're talent-rich. Jackpot. The insistence that he is an everyman is very inspiring but not very true. It's reminiscent of Steve Prefontaine, who was wont to downplay his own natural talents. <br />Here we have a humble hero who wins largely because he is simply more clever than most and more athletic than many. Don't let the roly-poly goofball silliness fool you: Foley was a very good wrestler. What made him a "great" was his understanding of theater, story, motivation, character, and business - all of which is in display in his writing.<br /><br />There. Nitpick over. Enjoy.</span>
  <a data-text-id="10515671098963147936" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


