    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3138228862" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3138228862" />
    <a title="Jason" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/4014393-jason"><img alt="Jason" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1619491193p2/4014393.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3138228862?book_show_action=true">Jan 12, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Jason" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Jason" href="/user/show/4014393-jason">Jason</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Hardcover 9780060392994" href="/book/show/218496.Have_a_Nice_Day_">review of another edition</a>

          <div><span class="uitext greyText">Recommends it for: </span>
           <span class="uitext reviewText">Wrestling Fans</span></div>

          <div>
    <span class="greyText">Recommended to Jason by: </span>
      Nobody
  </div>


          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4014393-jason?shelf=autographed">autographed</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4014393-jason?shelf=memoir-bio">memoir-bio</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3138228862" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7158200316191736263">In two months it&apos;ll have been two decades since I read this, and I remember only a little bit about it. However, I remember that I liked it, and that should be good enough to justify the four stars I give it... although I&apos;ve been <a href='https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/117193524' title='my review of Silver on the Tree' rel='nofollow noopener'>mistaken with that before</a>. Also, I must confess that I was a WWF fan back when I read this. Yes, back then it was WWF. This was before the wretched, loathsome, detestable World Wildlife Fund (or World Wide Fund for Nature [or World Wide Fuckheads]) sued them for sole us</span>
  <span id="freeText7158200316191736263" style="display:none">In two months it'll have been two decades since I read this, and I remember only a little bit about it. However, I remember that I liked it, and that should be good enough to justify the four stars I give it... although I've been <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/117193524" title="my review of Silver on the Tree" rel="nofollow noopener">mistaken with that before</a>. Also, I must confess that I was a WWF fan back when I read this. Yes, back then it was WWF. This was before the wretched, loathsome, detestable World Wildlife Fund (or World Wide Fund for Nature [or World Wide Fuckheads]) sued them for sole use of the acronym. Yeah, I know they do noble work, or something, but I'm petty and don't care. Besides, they're rather Machiavellian in their tactics, and here's <a href="https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/tomwarren/wwf-world-wide-fund-nature-parks-torture-death" rel="nofollow noopener">an article</a> about how terrible they can be. Don't hurt the animals, but kill all the civilians you want, and we'll cover it up like Nixon with Watergate. It might be fake news for all I know (though I don't believe that), but I don't give a fuck, they can... Actually, I'll let D'Generation X take it from here.<br><br><a href="https://imgur.com/FNjxBlg" rel="nofollow noopener">
  <img src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1578868890i/28765272.jpg" class="gr-hostedUserImg">
</a><br>"<b>SUCK IT!</b>"<br><br>Thanks. Anyway, I was a wrestling fan when I read this, I say, and I'm sure that affected how much I enjoyed the book. Mankind was my favorite wrestler with The Rock and Stone Cold Steve Austin close behind him. Plus Mick Foley (Mankind's real name) wrote it himself without a ghostwriter, and that's impressive. I later learned that a lot of wrestlers are actually quite intelligent, and nothing like the doofusy jerks they sometimes portray. I used to work with someone who worked for the WWF and knew all of them in the late 90's and early 00's, and she gave me the skinny on some of my faves. I also had the chance to meet Mick Foley a few years later at another job where he happened to be one of our donors.<br><br><a href="https://imgur.com/wz8WLzb" rel="nofollow noopener">
  <img src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1578868890i/28765273._SX540_.jpg" class="gr-hostedUserImg">
</a><br>(June, 2009... Wow, was that really over 10 years ago? Dag.)<br><br>He was the nicest guy, quite articulate, consented to shoot the shit with me for a few minutes, and everything; nothing like you'd expect from a professional wrestler. I mean, if you make your living kicking ass, how nice can you be? But those are just characters they portray, and like other actors, they're often completely different in real life.<br><br>Mankind put so much into his performances that he often set the bar for stunts in a wrestling match. In fact, he set it so high that they had to scale it back some after he left. The <a href="https://www.thesun.co.uk/sport/3920356/wwe-undertaker-mankind-hell-in-a-cell/" rel="nofollow noopener">1998 Hell in a Cell match</a> match was so insane that it was impossible to top, and it remains the most legendary match in WWF/WWE history. After that, he began to tone it down just a little bit (the alternative would have to lead to paralysis or death), but he still continued to give it his all until he retired.<br><br>Here's what Foley's dedication to his craft had cost him up to late 1999: 2/3 of his right ear ripped off, eight concussions, nose broken twice, a broken jaw, dislocated left shoulder, fractured left shoulder, broken left thumb, five broken ribs, a bruised kidney, broken left toe, over 325 stitches (54 of them for one injury in his left arm), torn meniscus, torn abdominal, broken right wrist, bone chips in his right elbow, two herniated discs, second degree burns on his right arm and shoulder, separated right shoulder, broken cheekbone, and four front teeth knocked out (one lodged in his nostril in the aforementioned Hell in a Cell match). And that's not counting the thousands of cuts and punctures he got from barbed wire, thumbtacks, and the like. More injuries came after this, but I don't feel like looking them up, and I'm sure they're listed in one of his follow-up books.<br><br>A lot of people say wrestling is fake, but I feel like this is inaccurate and does the profession a disservice. I suppose it depends on how you define fake. Saying it is "staged" is closer to the mark. The results are predetermined, a few moves are mapped out, and mostly they take their cues from the referee who is calling out what they're supposed to do next, which is kind of funny when you think about it. (Something I learned from this book, I think.) "Fake" makes it sound like there's no effort or cost involved. The list of injuries above shows there's certainly a cost, and as for effort, I'd like to see you perform any of the stunts these nutters do. One's body has to be in peak physical condition to even try some of those maneuvers, let alone pull them off. Using the aforementioned Hell in a Cell match as a case in point, Mankind lost the feeling in some of his fingers for two weeks just from climbing up to the top of the cage. That was at the very beginning of the match, and it just went downhill from there in terms of the physical toll. But the entertainment value? That's unmatched by anything else I've ever seen in wrestling, not that I've watched much of it since 2001 or thereabouts. It seems to have declined since then. I still check it out once a year or so, and either it's just not the same, or I've moved on.<br><br>Here are a couple of things I remember from the book. Wrestlers don't make anywhere near as much money as you'd think they do, even the superstars. (That might be different now.) He or one of the other people he was riding with to a match held in a fart for hours because there was a woman in the car which proves that wrestlers can be gentlemen too. People were always calling him by the wrong name, even his wife when she first met him. He's a really decent human being. (Anybody can make that claim, but he didn't. It just kind of shows in his writing.) He rarely cusses, or at least almost never drops the F bomb, but he opens the book with that bit of profanity. (And really, what else can you say when your ear is ripped off?) I think that happened in Japan or Germany or some other enemy state where the ring ropes are made of steel instead of... whatever they're made of here. Japs weren't as excitable as Americans during a match, and tended to watch quietly, saying something like "OOGAH!" when a particularly good move was done, but they were a much better and more appreciative audience than Americans... And that's all I got. And since these memories are 20 years in the rear view mirror, I wonder if any of them are true.<br><br>I read this while I was on spring break in Florida in 2000. I didn't do the college spring break; I was visiting my uncle with my father. Back then my uncle drove the same lime green VW bug that Mandy Moore drives in her "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=NkVsJGl5d6E" rel="nofollow noopener">Candy</a>" video. I don't care for the song all that much (in fact it annoyed the hell out of me on MTV when it came out), but I remember I thought the skateboarder with the blue shirt was really cute. What does this have to do with the book? Nothing at all, but this is my canvas, and I'll paint what I want, thank you very much.<br><br>Recommended for wrestling fans only. As much as I enjoyed it, I really can't think of anyone else who would like it because I think there's a lot of blow-by-blow commentary for several matches. The other stuff would interest other people, but you have to deal with the match stuff along the way.</span>
  <a data-text-id="7158200316191736263" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


