  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_487840438" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/487840438" />
    <a title="Leo H" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/8676838-leo-h"><img alt="Leo H" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1348503565p2/8676838.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/487840438?book_show_action=true">Dec 28, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Leo H" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Leo H" href="/user/show/8676838-leo-h">Leo H</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer487840438" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1435393093032601418">A fascinating study of the real/fake, painful/for sissies, sport/performance that is professional wrestling, written by a man who has quite literally been there, done that and got his own range of branded t-shirts. Quite surprising is the fact that this was written without a ghostwriter, very surprising is the fact that at the time of writing the book Foley didn&apos;t know how to use a computer, so all of the 700-odd pages were hand-written, longhand, onto pads of notepaper. The astonishing thing is</span>
  <span id="freeText1435393093032601418" style="display:none">A fascinating study of the real/fake, painful/for sissies, sport/performance that is professional wrestling, written by a man who has quite literally been there, done that and got his own range of branded t-shirts. Quite surprising is the fact that this was written without a ghostwriter, very surprising is the fact that at the time of writing the book Foley didn't know how to use a computer, so all of the 700-odd pages were hand-written, longhand, onto pads of notepaper. The astonishing thing is the fact that a man who has taken more steel chairs to the skull than I've had hot dinners can remember in such intricate detail events that happened years previously, how he felt, how other people felt, how it affected his career, and so on.<br /><br />One of the most interesting things about this book is placing it into the context of what was happening in professional wrestling at the time it was written and published. Around this time, circa 1999, the infamous 'Monday Night Wars' were in full swing, with WWF's Monday Night Raw going toe to toe with WCW's Monday Nitro. Admittedly by this point WWF had a massive lead, but the rivallry was still in full effect, and it's interesting to consider this when reading the sections of 'Have A Nice Day' in which Foley worked for WCW, having then left and joined WWF. He describes his time there as immensely frustrating, both creatively and personally, with WCW bookers and higher management both treating him incredibly poorly. He describes his main event push as being 'set up to fail', with Ric Flair, Arn Anderson and Bill Watts all putting him down and doubting his abilities. One wonders how much of this criticism comes from Foley himself and how much was exaggurated to put down the WWF's major opposition at the time. Something to think about, anyway.<br /><br />Foley describes his early work in wrestling in great detail, talking about the many small companies he worked for before hitting the big time. These passages are particularly interesting for me, as a wrestling fan with very little knowledge of the so-called 'territories era', in which wrestling promoters or companies would effectively split the US into sections, each promoting their company which that region and not spreading into other territories. This led to situations where wrestlers were treated as gods within their own territory (the Von Erichs in Dallas, for instance) but be virtual unknowns just a couple of states away. Foley came into wrestling just at the end of this era, as the NWA (the National Wrestling Alliance, which most territories were a part of and allowed for the trading of talent, settled disputes, elected an NWA World Heavyweight Champion from among the champions within the territories, sent this champ around the territories to fight local favourites to increase audiences, all that fun stuff) was in the process of being taken over solely by WCW, and it's quite sad to see this outlaw, PT Barnham style method of promotion slowly die through the eyes of a rookie wrestler, especially when I know so little about it in it's heyday and there are so few books and documentaries I can learn about it from. I realise this is a bit of a tangent, but the territorial era of American pro-wrestling is something that really fascinates me and there is very little material for me to devour on it. The reason there's no material on it? The WWE own all the back catalogues, and are doing fuck all with them. Or if they are, they highlight where these other companies went wrong or were run by idiots or crooks, as opposed to the WWF/E, which has never done anything wrong ever. So you understand my reticence to believe everything Mick Foley says of WCW in this book.<br /><br />Not that WCW were perfect of course, their treatment of Foley's face run as Cactus Jack against Big Van Vader is something which he discusses in depth in the book, and contains numerous examples of WCW bookers and writers dropping the ball on what could've been a shit hot feud between two of the greatest wrestlers in the 90s (in terms of psychology anyway, no-ones going to argue Foley has the technical ability of a Ricky Steamboat or a Chris Benoit). This feud demonstrates Foley's utter comittment to pro wrestling, it's scary to realise that in their first encounter on WCW Saturday Night on 6 April '93 (I'd link to the match but Youtube've taken it down), as Vader punches Cactus squarely in the face and you hear his nose break, Foley ASKED Vader to do that. Vader, who was regarded as one of the toughest wrestlers going at the time, to the point where (apparently) if a rookie wrestler arrived for a show and discovered he was fighting Vader, a lot of the time he would just quit the business on the spot and walk out. He was notorious for wrestling 'stiff', as in actually punching you and hurting you in a match, and at one point paralysed a young wrestler from the waist down for several weeks. According to several sources however he's a big sensitive puppy, bursting into tears after the aforementioned incident. Anyway, he's a brilliant heel. Possibly the best monster heel of all time. And somehow, Cactus Jack was a face, the fans being impressed by his ability not to feel pain, or something. After they met on April 6th, they wrestled again on April 24th, a match which ended with Vader power-bombing Cactus on the conctrete floor, putting him out for a kayfabe (storyline, not real) injury.<br /><br />This 'injury' gave Foley some time off, and he presumed that WCW would use this time to build up to his big comeback match with Vader at Halloween Havoc, in his first head-lining slot in a Pay-Per-View. Instead they embarked upon a bizarre angle whereby Cactus get amnesia from his injury, goes to a mental home, and befriends a ragtag bunch of crazy misfits. Why? Why do this? The fans don't want to see it, and it makes Cactus Jack look like a joke. However! On a point I've just thought of, this is interesting in comparison to Foley's run as Mankind in the WWF, which we''l look at in a bit.<br /><br />Understandably, Foley leaves WCW not long after this, to pursue a career wrestling for the 'indys', as they are known now. The promotion he worked for most frequently during this period, Extreme Championship Wrestling, is arguably where he did the best work of his career, especially in terms of psychology, as anyone who has seen the stunning 'Cane Dewey' promo (see here: <a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=28KH9YiJ9DI">http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=28KH9Y...</a>) in which Cactus Jack attempts to convince a fellow wrestler, Tommy Dreamer to take a chance to work at WCW, and turns on the ECW fans after seeing a sign with "Cane Dewey" (Dewey being his then 3-year old son) written on it in the crowd, can attest. Foley's absolutely perfect gaugeing of the "us vs. them" attitude of the ECW fans meant that by 'sucking up' to WWF and WCW he could raise their ire like no other heel at the company. This disdain of the ECW fans, who asked too much of their wrestlers, and frustration at not being able to hold a spot at a major company came from a real place within Foley, and he chanelled this frustration into his promos, which made this run all the more watchable, all the more vital, all the more believable, all the more unmissable. <br /><br />Foley was then hired by the WWF, where after 10 years he gave up the Cactus Jack character (at the behest of Vince MacMahon, obv) and became Mankind, who was originally a very dark, disturbed character who pulled out his own hair and stabbed himself in the leg with a pencil when he became frustrated (watch the highlight reel of Foley's Hall of Fame induction to see the most inappropriate use of backing music ever, as footage like this is shown with 'Hall of Fame' by The Script plays in the background), but over time became more of a comedy character. This shift was for several reasons, partially because Foley's slightly suicidal style was taking its toll on his body and he wanted to tone it down, and also the psychological elements of his gimmick just weren't going over with fans in the Attitude Era, who, in Foley's own words, largely just wanted swearing and catchphrases. So he caved in, and turned Mankind into (effectively) a big kid, who kept a sock in his trousers to shove down people's throats. What a change from the man who, 5 years earlier, was frustrated and disappointed by a company who belittled and degraded the character he had spent so long building up. Perhaps, reading between the lines, Foley knew he was coming to the end of his active career, and having spent several years as a midcarder at the WWF, he was just happy to make money, and that fans were getting behind him finally. Which is fair enough, I suppose, if a little disappointing considering the stellar work he did both at the WWF and elsewhere. <br /><br />So in conclusion, this is a great book. Excellently written, funny and interesting. As a wrestling fan I found it fascinating, and I think non-wrestling fans would get a great deal out of it as well. Highly recommended.</span>
  <a data-text-id="1435393093032601418" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


